				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">All right, I guess &quot;structures-of-arrays are faster&quot; was an oversimplification. The case I was thinking of was where you're only accessing one member of each structure in your loop. What matters is that data that you access sequentially is sequential in memory, so that you can use postincrement as much as possible and minimize the instructions spent recalculating addresses. So you'd definitely put the bytes of an array of 16/24/32-bit integers together, not interleave them like you might on a 6502. But if you've got one loop that does collision detection and another loop that does animation and metasprite assembly, and the data sets used by those loops are disjoint, it would make sense to split your &quot;actors&quot; into two structs, one with the collision detection data and the other with the animation data.</div>

